commitResults.messageBody: Originally the OwnerCard will manually retrieve each property (address, email, etc) manually. As a lot of these properties are specific to the type of Entity, this is not ideal for abstraction purposes. Thus it is necessary to let Entity class be able to return the properties and reduce reliance on the specific classes.

commitResults.messageTitle: Switch to Entity instead of Owner for storage and AddressBook
commitResults.messageBody:
AddressBook no longer stores an addressbook of owners, but it is an
addressbook that can contain all entity types. Storage related classes
and tests are also updated as well to reflect the new changes.

The ID is unique across all entities since all of them are stored in the
same container and thus naturally they will not clash. Current
implementation is by using a list of pairs. This allows for the UI
portion of the code to be adapted to use the new ID instead of the
visible list index.

Future work will include recording the list of dog owned by one single
owner. This will also necessitate a check right after import from any
other list. Tests coverage also dropped by a lot, there is huge amount
of test code that can be updated or newly written.

commitResults.messageTitle: Verify that the ID requested to be deleted is indeed an owner
Make it possible to delete dogs as well
Refactor JsonAdaptedEntity into individual child classes
commitResults.messageBody:
Originally JsonAdaptedEntity is a single class that represents all types
of entities. This caused a lot of restrictions since every entity has
other unique attributes that cannot be easily captured this way,
necessitating an additional method to return the extra attributes. It
added additional complexity when restoring the entities from json while
introducing an extra method that no other parts of the program uses.

The solution here is to create the child classes, JsonAdaptedOwner and
JsonAdaptedEntity. Jackson is able to store this additional information
with a few more annotations. This makes all of the JSON adaptation of
the various entities mirror their counterparts. Also the JSON file has
been renamed to "pawbook.json" as well, aligning with the project name
along with the actual content and avoiding the potential conflicts with
the previous file format.

The getOtherPropertiesAsDict method was introduced for JsonAdaptedEntity
to be able to be able to represent every entity and retrieve all of
their type specific attributes. Now that the JSON adapted version are
parallel versions of the original entities, the method is now redundant.

Update JsonAdaptedOwner to ensure that the dog IDs are stored
Ensure that referenced IDs are all valid upon import
commitResults.messageBody:
Owners store the IDs of the dogs they own and dogs store the ID of their
owner. While the application is running it should be guaranteed that
all of these information is kept updated and always valid. But there is
no guarantee when importing from an external source.

It is therefore necessary verify that all the dog IDs referenced by an
owner are valid dogs in the list and all owner IDs reference by a dog
are valid owners. There is also a need to verify that these links are
mutual.

commitResults.messageBody:
This reverts commit 33f98c75a2b829ada9c1393add82696ce0b5c2c6, reversing
changes made to 82b5796538876e6a98a9046a4b5bae3ff807300b.

Previously when CommandWithPrefixParser was generalised out of
AddCommandParser, it catered to the needs of commands that use prefixes,
out of which some are compulsory prefixes and has preamble. Some
commands like edit do not have compulsory prefixes or preamble, thus it
is necessary to further simplify it for such use cases.

Fix bug where delete will fail when entity not visible
commitResults.messageBody:
The bug occurred due to delete commands manually matching the target ID
against the filtered list, resulting in the commands being unable to
find the correct entity even when it truly exists. The fix here is to
make use of the standardised methods from model to perform the matching
and retrieval, avoiding raw use of the underlying list of entities.
